title: For Sale/Trade:  Finnish Mosin Nagant M91 With Ammo & Stripper Clips
postcontent: Not your typical Russian Mosin Nagant. This is the better made Finnish Mosin Nagant M91 (not the common M91/30). The Model 91 is an older version of the M91/30, which has the longer barrel. This gun has matching numbers, or Finn match (matching numbers on the barrel shank and bolt knob). Made in 1940 by VKT (later known as Valmet). Bore is good,not counterbored like a lot of the Mosin Nagants out there. However, the bore is kind of dark (probably just need a really good cleaning, or need to shoot the gun to get the bore clean. I have not fire the gun). But has good lands and grooves. Stock is in good condition. No cracks, splits, or damages. Overall, this rifle is in good to very good condition. Comes with 200 or so rounds of surplus ammo in two sealed cans and stripper clips. Just email me for more informations/questions. Or, you can do a google (or yahoo) search on Finnish Mosin Nagants. There are plenty of informations on the internet on this particular gun. I apologize for the quality of the pictures. The rifle is much better looking in person than the pictures. I used my cameraphone to take the pics. And it does not take really good pics. Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  RWS MODEL 46 W/ RWS SCOPE
postcontent:
Shoots great and I would say a 99% gun steel and stock both. the curent model (460) goes for $600.00 + see below.

 http://www.amazon.com/Diana-RWS-Magnum-Combo-rifle/dp/B000R4JJ8S/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=REDACTED&sr=8-1

The RWS Model 46 E is a well made rifle. Very well engineered with smooth parts operation. Solid and safe design and most importantly it's very accurate and smooth in operation. After operating some of the other underlever rifles I really appreciate the safety in the loading port - much easier to load than the Mag 460. It's well designed and thought out and most importantly it's accurate and no "Droop." This is one of the most accurate rifles I own with solid 1 hole touching the next in 5 shot groups.

Fit and finish
Diana has always had a good fit and finish, but it's never quite up to the standards of Weihrauch. Perhaps, it's more in the BSA class. Since the 46 was targeted to go after the British TX, they went out of their way to make as crisp a rifle as they could. The lines are very clean and the cheekpiece is quite stylish and well-shaped - an area where other Dianas perhaps fall short. The stock has the typical Diana angularity, compared to the more rounded TX. It also shaves off about a pound of weight, making the 46 the lighter rifle.

The easiest way to accomplish this is to set the butt on the ground and push the barrel down, often pointing the muzzle at the shooter.  Winchester realized the flaw in the design and offered a new Model 12 for all Model 11's turned in, but continued to sell the Model 11 until 1925.
